  "prompt": "What is the stage 2 hypertension diet?",
  "response": "The stage 2 hypertension diet is focused on managing high blood pressure through healthy eating practices. A well-known approach is the DASH (Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension) diet. Here are some key components of the diet:\n\n1. **Fruits and Vegetables**: Increase intake of a variety of fruits and vegetables. Aim for 4-5 servings of each per day.\n\n2. **Whole Grains**: Choose whole grains over refined grains. This includes eating whole-grain bread, pasta, and cereal.\n\n3. **Lean Proteins**: Incorporate lean protein sources such as poultry, fish, beans, and nuts. Limit red meat consumption.\n\n4. **Low-Fat Dairy**: Consume low-fat or fat-free dairy products to reduce saturated fat intake.\n\n5. **Limit Salt**: Aim to consume less than 2,300 mg of sodium per day, or ideally 1,500 mg, especially for those with high blood pressure.\n\n6. **Healthy Fats**: Use healthy fats, such as those found in olive oil, nuts, and avocados, and limit saturated and trans fats.\n\n7. **Reduce Added Sugars**: Limit consumption of foods and drinks with added sugars.\n\n8. **Control Portions**: Be mindful of portion sizes to maintain a healthy weight.\n\n9. **Limit Alcohol**: If you drink alcohol, do so in moderation. For men, up to two drinks per day, and for women, one drink per day.\n\n10. **Regular Physical Activity**: Alongside dietary changes, engage in regular physical activity as part of a comprehensive approach to health.\n\nIt's important to consult with a healthcare provider or a registered dietitian before making major changes to your diet, especially if you have stage 2 hypertension, as they can provide guidance tailored to your specific health needs.",
